04208nam a22005775i 9780271092041DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710920417 a10.1515/97802710920412doi  a(DE-B1597)619115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041202bisacsh1 aCooper-Rompato, Christine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpiritual Calculations :bNumber and Numeracy in Late Medieval English Sermons /cChristine Cooper-Rompato. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Encountering the Divine Through Number in Middle English Sermons -- t2. Numbers in Dives and Pauper and the Sermons of Warminster, Longleat House MS 4 -- t3. “Knowing Thyself ” and God Through Number in Jacob’s Well -- t4. Quantitative Reasoning in the Latin Sermons of Robert Rypon in London, British Library, MS Harley 4894 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Methods of Counting and Calculation in the Later Middle Ages -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMedieval English sermons teem with examples of quantitative reasoning, ranging from the arithmetical to the numerological, and regularly engage with numerical concepts. Examining sermons written in Middle English and Latin, this book reveals that popular English-speaking audiences were encouraged to engage in a wide range of numerate operations in their daily religious practices.Medieval sermonists promoted numeracy as a way for audiences to appreciate divine truth. Their sermons educated audiences in a hybrid form of numerate practice—one that relied on individuals’ pragmatic quantitative reasoning, which, when combined with spiritual interpretations of numbers provided by the preacher, created a deep and rich sense in which number was the best way to approach the sacred mysteries of the world as well as to learn how one could best live as a Christian. Analyzing both published and previously unpublished sermons and sermon cycles, Christine Cooper-Rompato explores the use of numbers, arithmetic, and other mathematical operations to better understand how medieval laypeople used math as a means to connect with God.Spiritual Calculations enhances our understanding of medieval sermons and sheds new light on how receptive audiences were to this sophisticated rhetorical form. It will be welcomed by scholars of Middle English literature, medieval sermon studies, religious experience, and the history of mathematics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076692940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271092041zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271092041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271092041/original  a978-3-11-076692-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK